# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smith-chart-matching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Antenna tuners are particularly important for use with transmitters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Transmitters feed power into a resistive load, very often 50 ohms, for which the transmitter is optimally designed for power output, efficiency, and low distortion.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If the load seen by the transmitter departs from this design value due to improper tuning of the antenna/feedline combination the power output will change, distortion may occur and the transmitter may overheat.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] ATUs are a standard part of almost all radio transmitters; they may be a circuit included inside the transmitter itself or a separate piece of equipment connected between the transmitter and the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In transmitters in which the antenna is mounted separate from the transmitter and connected to it by a transmission line (feedline), there may be a second ATU (or matching network) at the antenna to match the impedance of the antenna to the transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In low power transmitters with attached antennas, such as cell phones and walkie-talkies, the ATU is fixed to work with the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In high power transmitters like radio stations, the ATU is adjustable to accommodate changes in the antenna or transmitter, and adjusting the ATU to match the transmitter to the antenna is an important procedure done after any changes to these components have been made.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This adjustment is done with an instrument called a SWR meter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In radio receivers ATUs are not so important, because in the lower-frequency parts of the radio spectrum the signal to noise ratio (SNR) is dominated by atmospheric noise.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] It does not matter if the impedance of the antenna and receiver are mismatched so some of the incoming power from the antenna is reflected and does not reach the receiver, because the signal can be amplified to make up for it.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However, in high frequency receivers the receiver's SNR is dominated by noise in the receiver's front end, so it is important that the receiving antenna is impedance-matched to the receiver to give maximum signal amplitude in the front end stages, to overcome noise.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] An antenna's impedance is different at different frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] An antenna tuner matches a radio with a fixed impedance (typically 50 ohms for modern transceivers) to the *combination* of the feedline and the antenna; useful when the impedance seen at the input end of the feedline is unknown, complex, or otherwise different from the transceiver.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Coupling through an ATU allows the use of one antenna on a broad range of frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However, despite its name, an antenna *tuner* actually matches the transmitter only to the complex impedance reflected back to the input end of the feedline.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If both tuner and transmission line were lossless, tuning at the transmitter end would indeed produce a match at every point in the transmitter-feedline-antenna system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However, in practical systems feedline losses limit the ability of the antenna 'tuner' to match the antenna or change its resonant frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If the loss of power is very low in the line carrying the transmitter's signal into the antenna, a tuner at the transmitter end can produce a worthwhile degree of matching and tuning for the antenna and feedline network as a whole.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With lossy feedlines (such as commonly used 50 Ohm coaxial cable) maximum power transfer only occurs if matching is done at both ends of the line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If there is still a high SWR (multiple reflections) in the feedline beyond the ATU, any loss in the feedline is multiplied several times by the transmitted waves reflecting back and forth between the tuner and the antenna, heating the wire instead of sending out a signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Even with a matching unit at both ends of the feedline – the near ATU matching the transmitter to the feedline and the remote ATU matching the feedline to the antenna – losses in the circuitry of the two ATUs will reduce power delivered to the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Transformers, autotransformers, and baluns are sometimes incorporated into the design of narrow band antenna tuners and antenna cabling connections.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] They will all usually have little effect on the resonant frequency of either the antenna or the narrow band transmitter circuits, but can widen the range of impedances that the antenna tuner can match, and/or convert between balanced and unbalanced cabling where needed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Solid-state power amplifiers operating from 1–30 MHz typically use one or more wideband transformers wound on ferrite cores.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] MOSFETs and bipolar junction transistors are designed to operate into a low impedance, so the transformer primary typically has a single turn, while the 50 Ohm secondary will have 2 to 4 turns.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This feedline system design has the advantage of reducing the retuning required when the operating frequency is changed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A similar design can match an antenna to a transmission line; For example, many TV antennas have a 300 Ohm impedance and feed the signal to the TV via a 75 Ohm coaxial line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A small ferrite core transformer makes the broad band impedance transformation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This transformer does not need, nor is it capable of adjustment.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For receive-only use in a TV the small SWR variation with frequency is not a major problem.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] It should be added that many ferrite based transformers perform a balanced to unbalanced transformation along with the impedance change.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When the *bal*anced to *un*balanced function is present these transformers are called a **balun** (otherwise an **unun**).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The most common baluns have either a 1:1 or a 1:4 *impedance* transformation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] There are several designs for impedance matching using an autotransformer, which is a single-wire transformer with different connection points or *taps* spaced along the windings.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] They are distinguished mainly by their *impedance* transform ratio (1:1, 1:4, 1:9, etc., the square of the winding ratio), and whether the input and output sides share a common ground, or are matched from a cable that is grounded on one side (unbalanced) to an ungrounded (usually balanced) cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When autotransformers connect *bal*anced and *un*balanced lines they are called **balun**s, just as two-winding transformers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When two differently-grounded cables or circuits must be connected but the grounds kept independent, a full, two-winding transformer with the desired ratio is used instead.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The circuit pictured at the right has three identical windings wrapped in the same direction around either an "air" core (for very high frequencies) or ferrite core (for middle, or low frequencies).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The three equal windings shown are wired for a common ground shared by two unbalanced lines (so this design is called an **unun**), and can be used as 1:1, 1:4, or 1:9 impedance match, depending on the tap chosen.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For example, if the right-hand side is connected to a resistive load of 10 Ohms, the user can attach a source at any of the three ungrounded terminals on the left side of the autotransformer to get a different impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Notice that on the left side, the line with more windings measures greater impedance for the same 10 Ohm load on the right.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The "narrow-band" methods described below cover a very much smaller span of frequencies, by comparison with the broadband methods described above.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Antenna matching methods that use transformers tend to cover a wide range of frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A single, typical, commercially available balun can cover frequencies from 3.5–30.0 MHz, or nearly the entire shortwave radio band.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Matching to an antenna using a cut segment of transmission line (described below) is perhaps the most efficient of all matching schemes in terms of electrical power, but typically can only cover a range about 3.5–3.7 MHz wide – a very small range indeed, compared to a broadband balun.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Antenna coupling or feedline matching circuits are also narrowband for any single setting, but can be re-tuned more conveniently.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However they are perhaps the least efficient in terms of power-loss (aside from having no impedance matching at all!).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The insertion of a special section of transmission line, whose characteristic impedance differs from that of the main line, can be used to match the main line to the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] An inserted line with the proper impedance and connected at the proper location can perform complicated matching effects with very high efficiency, but spans a very limited frequency range.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The simplest example this method is the quarter-wave impedance transformer formed by a spliced section of mismatched transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If a quarter-wavelength of 75 Ohm coaxial cable is linked to a 50 Ohm load, the SWR in the 75 Ohm quarter wavelength of line can be calculated as 75Ω / 50Ω = 1.5; the quarter-wavelength of line transforms the mismatched impedance to 112.5 Ohms (75 Ohms × 1.5 = 112.5 Ohms).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Thus this inserted section matches a 112 Ohm antenna to a 50 Ohm main line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The ⁠1/6⁠ wave coaxial transformer is a useful way to match 50 to 75 Ohms using the same general method.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A second common method is the use of a stub: A shorted, or open section of line is connected in parallel with the main line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With coax this is done using a 'T'-connector.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The length of the stub and its location can be chosen so as to produce a matched line below the stub, regardless of the complex impedance or SWR of the antenna itself.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The J-pole antenna is an example of an antenna with a built-in stub match.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The basic circuit required when lumped capacitances and inductors are used is shown below.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This circuit is important in that many automatic antenna tuners use it, and also because more complex circuits can be analyzed as groups of L-networks.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This is called an L network not because it contains an inductor, (in fact some L-networks consist of two capacitors), but because the two components are at right angles to each other, having the shape of a rotated and sometimes reversed English letter 'L'.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The 'T' ("Tee") network and the π ("Pi") network also have a shape similar to the English and Greek letters they are named after.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This basic network is able to act as an impedance transformer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In this example circuit, *X*L and *X*C can be swapped.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] All the ATU circuits below create this network, which exists between systems with different impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A parallel network, consisting of a resistive element (1000 Ω) and a reactive element (−*j* 229.415 Ω), will have the same impedance and power factor as a series network consisting of resistive (50 Ω) and reactive elements (−*j* 217.94 Ω).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] By adding another element in series (which has a reactive impedance of +*j* 217.94 Ω), the impedance is 50 Ω (resistive).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The 'L'-network can have eight different configurations, six of which are shown here.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The two missing configurations are the same as the bottom row, but with the parallel element (wires vertical) on the right side of the series element (wires horizontal), instead of on the left, as shown.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In discussion of the diagrams that follows the **in** connector comes from the transmitter or "source"; the **out** connector goes to the antenna or "load".
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The general rule (with some exceptions, described below) is that the series element of an 'L'-network goes on the side with the lowest impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The top two circuits in the right column, with the series (horizontal) element on the **in** side, are generally useful for **step**ping **down** from a higher input to a lower output impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The general rule only applies to loads that are mainly resistive, with very little reactance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In cases where the load is highly reactive – such as an antenna fed with a signal whose frequency is far away from any resonance – the opposite configuration may be required.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If far from resonance, the bottom two **step down** (high-in to low-out) circuits would instead be used to connect for a step up (low-in to high-out that is mostly reactance).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The low- and high-pass versions of the four circuits shown in the top two rows use only one inductor and one capacitor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The **Low *R*, high *C*** circuit is shown feeding a short vertical antenna, such as would be the case for a compact, mobile antenna or otherwise on frequencies below an antenna's lowest natural resonant frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Here the inherent capacitance of a short, random wire antenna is so high that the 'L'-network is best realized with two inductors, instead of aggravating the problem by using a capacitor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The **Low *R*, high *L*** circuit is shown feeding a small loop antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Below resonance this type of antenna has so much inductance, that more inductance from adding a coil would make the reactance even worse.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Therefore, the 'L'-network is composed of two capacitors.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Radio operators must experiment and test the available settings, and use informed judgement to choose the best among those possible adjustments that can all match the same impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Every means of impedance match will introduce some power loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This will vary from a few percent for a transformer with a ferrite core, to 50% or more for a complex ATU that is improperly tuned or working at the limits of its tuning range.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With the narrow band tuners, the 'L'-network has the lowest loss, partly because it has the fewest components, but mainly because it necessarily operates at the lowest possible Q value for a given impedance transformation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With the 'L'-network, the loaded Q is not adjustable, but is fixed midway between the source and load impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Since most of the loss in practical tuners will be in the coil (inductor), choosing between either the low-pass or high-pass network for lowest needed inductance may reduce the loss somewhat.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The 'L'-network using only capacitors will have the lowest loss, but this network only works where the load impedance is very inductive, making it a good choice for a small loop antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Inductive impedance also occurs with straight-wire antennas used at frequencies slightly above a resonant frequency, where the antenna is too long – for example, between a quarter and a half wave long at the operating frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However, problematic straight-wire antennas are typically too short for the frequency in use.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With the high-pass 'T'-network, the loss in the tuner can vary from a few percent – if tuned for lowest loss – to over 50% if the tuner is not properly adjusted.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Using the maximum available capacitance will give less loss, than if one simply tunes for a match without regard for the settings.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] This is because using more capacitance means using fewer inductor turns, and the loss is mainly in the inductor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With the SPC tuner the losses will be somewhat higher than with the 'T'-network, since the added capacitance across the inductor will shunt some reactive current to ground which must be cancelled by additional current in the inductor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The trade-off is that the effective inductance of the coil is increased, thus allowing operation at lower frequencies than would otherwise be possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] If additional filtering is desired, the inductor can be deliberately set to larger values, thus providing a partial band pass effect.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Either the high-pass 'T', low-pass 'π', or the SPC tuner can be adjusted in this manner.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The additional attenuation at harmonic frequencies can be increased significantly with only a small percentage of additional loss at the tuned frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When adjusted for minimum loss, the SPC tuner will have better harmonic rejection than the high-pass 'T' due to its internal tank circuit being a bandpass filter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Either type is capable of good harmonic rejection if a small additional loss is acceptable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The low-pass 'π' has exceptional harmonic attenuation at *any* setting, including the lowest-loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] An ATU will be inserted somewhere along the line connecting the radio transmitter or receiver to the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The antenna feedpoint is usually high in the air (for example, a dipole antenna) or far away (for example, an end-fed random wire antenna).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A transmission line, or feedline, must carry the signal between the transmitter and the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The ATU can be placed anywhere along the feedline: at the transmitter, at the antenna, or somewhere in between.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Antenna tuning is best done as close to the antenna as possible to minimize loss, increase bandwidth, and reduce peak voltage and peak current on the transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Also, when the information being transmitted has frequency components whose wavelength is a significant fraction of the electrical length of the feed line, distortion of the transmitted information will occur if there are standing waves on the line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Analog TV and FM stereo broadcasts are affected in this way.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For those modes, matching at the antenna is required.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When possible, an automatic or remotely-controlled tuner in a weather-proof case at or near the antenna is convenient and makes for an efficient system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] With such a tuner, it is possible to match a wide range of antennas.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When the ATU must be located near the radio for convenient adjustment, any significant SWR will increase the loss in the feedline.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For that reason, when using an ATU at the transmitter, low-loss, high-impedance feedline is a great advantage (open-wire line, for example).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A short length of low-loss coaxial line is acceptable, but with longer lossy lines the additional loss due to SWR becomes very high.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] It is very important to remember that when matching the transmitter to the line, as is done when the ATU is near the transmitter, there is no change in the SWR in the feedline.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The backlash currents reflected from the antenna are retro-reflected by the ATU – usually several times between the two – and so are invisible on the transmitter-side of the ATU.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The result of the multiple reflections is compounded loss, higher voltage or higher currents, and narrowed bandwidth, none of which can be corrected by the ATU.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] It is a common misconception that a high standing wave ratio (SWR) *per se* causes loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] A well-adjusted ATU feeding an antenna through a low-loss line may have only a small percentage of additional loss compared with an intrinsically matched antenna, even with a high SWR (4 to 1, for example).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] An ATU sitting beside the transmitter just re-reflects energy reflected from the antenna ("backlash current") back yet again, along the feedline to the antenna ("retro-reflection").
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] High losses arise from RF resistance in the feedline and antenna, and those multiple reflections due to high SWR cause feedline losses to be compounded.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Using high-impedance, low-loss feedline with an ATU results in very little loss, even with multiple reflections.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] However, if the feedline-antenna combination is 'lossy' then an identical high SWR may lose a considerable fraction of the transmitter's power output.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] High impedance lines – such as most parallel-wire lines with impedances between 300–500 Ω – carry power mostly as high voltage rather than high current, and current alone determines the power lost to line resistance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] So despite high SWR, very little power is lost in high-impedance line compared low-impedance line, such as typical 50 Ω coaxial cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For that reason, radio operators transmitting through high-impedance feedline can be more casual about where and if they use an ATU.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Without an ATU, the SWR from a mismatched antenna and feedline can present an improper load to the transmitter, causing distortion and loss of power or efficiency with heating and / or burning of the output stage components.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Modern solid state transmitters will automatically reduce power when they detect high SWR, so some solid-state power stages only produce weak signals if the SWR rises above 1.5 to 1 (1.5:1).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Were it not for the problem of automatic power-reduction, even the losses from an SWR of 2:1 could be tolerated, since only 11 percent of transmitted power would be reflected and 89 percent sent out through to the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] So the main loss of output power with high SWR is due to the transmitter "backing off" its output when challenged with backlash current.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Tube transmitters and amplifiers usually have an adjustable output network that can feed mismatched loads up to perhaps 3:1 SWR without trouble.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] In effect the built-in π-network of the transmitter output stage acts as an ATU.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Further, since tubes are electrically robust (even though mechanically fragile), tube-based circuits can tolerate very high backlash current without damage.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] One of the oldest applications for antenna tuners is in AM and shortwave broadcasting transmitters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] AM transmitters usually use a vertical antenna (tower) which can be from 0.20 to 0.68 wavelengths long.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] At the base of the tower an ATU is used to match the antenna to the 50 Ohm transmission line from the transmitter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The most commonly used circuit is a T-network, using two series inductors with a shunt capacitor between them.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] When multiple towers are used the ATU network may also provide for a phase adjustment so that the currents in each tower can be phased relative to the others to produce a desired pattern.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] These patterns are often required by law to include nulls in directions that could produce interference as well as to increase the signal in the target area.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Adjustment of the ATUs in a multitower array is a complex and time-consuming process requiring considerable expertise.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] For International Shortwave (50 kW and above), frequent antenna tuning is done as part of frequency changes which may be required on a seasonal or even a daily basis.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Modern shortwave transmitters typically include built-in impedance-matching circuitry for SWR up to 2:1 , and can adjust their output impedance within 15 seconds.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The matching networks in transmitters sometimes incorporate a balun or an external one can be installed at the transmitter in order to feed a balanced line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Balanced transmission lines of 300 Ohms or more were more-or-less standard for all shortwave transmitters and antennas in the past, even by amateurs.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Most shortwave broadcasters have continued to use high-impedance feeds even before the advent of automatic impedance matching.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The most commonly used shortwave antennas for international broadcasting are the HRS antenna (curtain array), which cover a 2 to 1 frequency range and the log-periodic antenna which cover up to 8 to 1 frequency range.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Within that range, the SWR will vary, but is usually kept below 1.7 to 1 – within the range of SWR that can be tuned by antenna matching built-into many modern transmitters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Hence, when feeding these antennas, a modern transmitter will be able to tune itself as needed to match at any frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Automatic antenna tuning is used in flagship mobile phones, transceivers for amateur radio, and in land mobile, marine, and tactical HF radio transceivers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Each antenna tuning system (AT) shown in the figure has an "antenna port", which is directly or indirectly coupled to an antenna, and another port, referred to as "radio port" (or as "user port"), for transmitting and / or receiving radio signals through the AT and the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Each AT shown in the figure has a single antenna-port, (SAP) AT, but a multiple antenna-port (MAP) AT may be needed for MIMO radio transmission.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Several control schemes can be used in a radio transceiver or transmitter to automatically adjust an antenna tuner (AT).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The control schemes are based on one of the two configurations, (a) and (b), shown in the diagram.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The TSPU incorporates all the parts of the transmitting not otherwise shown in the diagram.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The TX port of the TSPU delivers a test signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The SU delivers, to the TSPU, one or more output signals indicating the response to the test signal, one or more electrical variables (such as voltage, current, incident or forward voltage, etc.).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] The response sensed at the *radio port* in the case of configuration (a) or at the *antenna port* in the case of configuration (b).
[src:smith-chart-matching/antenna-tuner] Note that neither configuration (a) nor (b) is ideal, since the line between the antenna and the AT attenuates SWR; response to a test signal is most accurately tested at or near the antenna feedpoint.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A **balun** /ˈbælʌn/ (from "balanced to unbalanced", originally, but now derived from "**balancing unit**") is an electrical device that allows balanced and unbalanced lines to be interfaced without disturbing the impedance arrangement of either line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun can take many forms and may include devices that also transform impedances but need not do so.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Sometimes, in the case of transformer baluns, they use magnetic coupling but need not do so.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Common-mode chokes are also used as baluns and work by eliminating, rather than rejecting, common mode signals.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In classical transformers, there are two electrically separate windings of wire coils around the transformer's core.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This type is sometimes called a 'voltage balun'.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The primary winding receives the input signal, and the secondary winding puts out the converted signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The core that they are wound on may either be empty (air core) or, equivalently, a magnetically neutral material like a porcelain support, or it may be a material which is good magnetic conductor like ferrite in modern high-frequency (HF) baluns, or soft iron as in the early days of telegraphy.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The electrical signal in the primary coil is converted into a magnetic field in the transformer's core.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] When the electrical current through the primary reverses, it causes the established magnetic field to collapse.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The collapsing magnetic field then induces an electric field in the secondary winding.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The ratio of loops in each winding and the efficiency of the coils' magnetic coupling determines the ratio of electrical potential (voltage) to electrical current and the total power of the output.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] For idealized transformers, although the ratio of voltage to current will change in exact proportion to the square of the winding ratio, the power (measured in watts) remains identical.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In real transformers, some energy is lost inside to heating of the metallic core of the transformer, to the AC and DC resistances of the winding conductors, and lost outside to the surrounding environment because of imperfect magnetic coupling between the two coils.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] An ideal balun consists of two wires (primary and secondary) and a core: the current in the primary wire generates a magnetic field in the core, which in turn induces an electric field in the secondary wire.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] An autotransformer balun has only one coil, or is made of two or more coils that have an electrical connection, wound around a core.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] One can also make an autotransformer from an ordinary transformer by cross-wiring the primary and secondary windings.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Baluns made with autotransformer windings are also called *voltage baluns*, since they produce balanced output voltage, but not necessarily balanced current.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In all autotransformers, the single winding must have at least one extra electrical connection – called a *tap* or *tap point* – between the two ends of the winding.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The current sent into the balun through one pair of connections acts as if it were a primary coil, and magnetizes the entire core.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] When the electric current in the input segment of the coil changes, the induced magnetic field collapses and the collapse of the magnetic field in the core induces an electric current in the entire coil.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Electrical connections to parts of the coil different from the input connections have higher or lower voltages depending on the length of the coil that the output is tapped from.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Unlike transformer-type baluns, an autotransformer balun provides a path for DC current to ground from every terminal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Since outdoor antennas are prone to build-up of static electric charge, the path for the static to drain to ground through an autotransformer balun can be a distinct advantage.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Transmission line or *choke* baluns can be considered as simple forms of transmission line transformers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This type is sometimes called a *current balun*, since it ensures equal current on both sides of its output, but not necessarily equal voltage.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] These are normally called ununs, because they go from unbalanced to unbalanced or un-un.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Baluns are balanced to unbalanced or bal-un.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A more subtle type results when the transformer type (magnetic coupling) is combined with the transmission line type (electro-magnetic coupling).
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Most typically the same kind of transmission line wires are used for the windings as carry the signal from the radio to the antenna, although these baluns can be made using any type of wire.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The resulting devices have very wideband operation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] *Transmission line transformers* commonly use small ferrite cores in toroidal rings or two-hole, binocular, shapes.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The Guanella transmission line transformer (Guanella 1944) is often combined with a balun to act as an impedance matching transformer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Putting balancing aside a transformer of this type consists of a 75 Ω transmission line divided in parallel into two 150 Ω cables, which are then combined in series for 300 Ω.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] It is implemented as a specific wiring around the ferrite core of the balun.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Classic magnetic transformers are limited in maximum frequency due to the permeability of the magnetic material, which declines rapidly above MHz frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This limits the operating frequency to around 1 GHz.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Microwave systems require baluns in the 1-100 GHz range for applications including mixers, push-pull amplifiers, and interface to differential analog to digital and digital to analog converters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Transmission line transformer baluns with a high frequency transmission line such as a wirewound pair are able to operate at significantly higher frequencies (to 8 GHz and above) by combining capacitive coupling with magnetic coupling typical of classic magnetic transformers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] To operate at even higher frequencies, magnetic loading becomes ineffective.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Nathan Marchand proposed a 'conversion transformer' that was capable of operation over a 1:3 bandwidth ratio in 1944.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This basic circuit has been widely adapted and modified for use in planar structures (such as MMICs and RFICs) at frequencies up to at least 100 GHz.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] These types of planar baluns work exciting a mode in a ground plane or shield, which is then 'floated' away from the main ground.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This allows extraction of the negative signal in addition to the main transmission line, creating positive and negative signal pairs.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] By connecting the positive and negative signal paths in various configurations dozens of balun configurations have been proposed and published in the electronics literature.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The electrical connection of capacitance and inductance leads to a frequency where the electrical reactance of the self-inductance and self-capacitance in the balun are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign: that is, to resonance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun of any design operates poorly at or above its self-resonant frequency, and some of the design considerations for baluns are for the purpose of making the resonant frequency as far above the operating frequency as possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] An RF choke can be used in place of a balun.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] If a coil is made using coaxial cable near to the feed point of a balanced antenna, then the RF current that flows on the outer surface of the coaxial cable can be attenuated.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] One way of doing this would be to pass the cable through a ferrite toroid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The end result is exactly the same as a 1:1 current balun (or Guanella-type balun).
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun's function is generally to achieve compatibility between systems, and as such, finds extensive application in modern communications, particularly in realising frequency conversion mixers to make cellular phone and data transmission networks possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] They are also used to send an E1 carrier signal from coaxial cable (BNC connector, 1.0/2.3 connector, 1.6/5.6 connector, Type 43 connectors) to UTP CAT-5 cable or IDC connector.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In television, amateur radio, and other antenna installations and connections, baluns convert between impedances and symmetry of feedlines and antennas.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] For example, transformation of 300-Ω twin-lead or 450-Ω ladder line (balanced) to 75-Ω coaxial cable (unbalanced), or to directly connect a balanced antenna to unbalanced coaxial cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] To avoid feed line radiation, baluns are typically used as a form of common mode choke attached at the antenna feed point to prevent the coaxial cable from acting as an antenna and radiating power.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This typically is needed when a balanced antenna (for instance, a dipole) is fed with coax; without a balun, the shield of the coax could couple with one side of the dipole, inducing common mode current, and becoming part of the antenna and unintentionally radiating.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In measuring the impedance or radiation pattern of a balanced antenna using a coaxial cable, it is important to place a balun between the cable and the antenna feed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Unbalanced currents that may otherwise flow on the cable will make the measured antenna impedance sensitive to the configuration of the feed cable, and the radiation pattern of small antennas may be distorted by radiation from the cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Baluns are present in radars, transmitters, satellites, in every telephone network, and probably in most wireless network modem/routers used in homes.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] It can be combined with transimpedance amplifiers to compose high-voltage amplifiers out of low-voltage components.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Baseband video uses frequencies up to several megahertz.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun can be used to couple video signals to twisted-pair cables instead of using coaxial cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Many security cameras now have both a balanced unshielded twisted pair (UTP) output and an unbalanced coaxial one via an internal balun.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun is also used on the video recorder end to convert back from the 100 Ω balanced to 75 Ω unbalanced.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A balun of this type has a BNC connector with two screw terminals.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] VGA/DVI baluns are baluns with electronic circuitry used to connect VGA/DVI sources (laptop, DVD, etc.) to VGA/DVI display devices over long runs of CAT-5/CAT-6 cable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Runs over 130 m (400 ft) may lose quality because of attenuation and variations in the arrival time of each signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A skew control and special low skew or skew free cable is used for runs over 130 m (400 ft).
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] In audio applications, baluns serve multiple purposes: they can convert between high-impedance unbalanced and low impedance balanced lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Another application is decoupling of devices (avoidance of earth loops).
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] A third application of baluns in audio systems is in the provision of balanced mains power to the equipment.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] This noise infiltrates the audio/video system through the power supplies and raises the noise floor of the entire system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] Except for the connections, the three devices in the image are electrically identical, but only the leftmost two can be used as baluns.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The device on the left would normally be used to connect a high impedance source, such as a guitar, into a balanced microphone input, serving as a passive DI unit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The one in the center is for connecting a low impedance balanced source, such as a microphone, into a guitar amplifier.
[src:smith-chart-matching/balun] The one at the right is not a balun, as it provides only impedance matching.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are most frequently constructed from two coupled transmission lines set close enough together such that energy passing through one is coupled to the other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This technique is favoured at the microwave frequencies where transmission line designs are commonly used to implement many circuit elements.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, lumped component devices are also possible at lower frequencies, such as the audio frequencies encountered in telephony.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Also at microwave frequencies, particularly the higher bands, waveguide designs can be used.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Many of these waveguide couplers correspond to one of the conducting transmission line designs, but there are also types that are unique to waveguide.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Directional couplers and power dividers have many applications.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] These include providing a signal sample for measurement or monitoring, feedback, combining feeds to and from antennas, antenna beam forming, providing taps for cable distributed systems such as cable TV, and separating transmitted and received signals on telephone lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The symbols most often used for directional couplers are shown in figure 1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The symbol may have the coupling factor in dB marked on it.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Port 1 is the input port where power is applied.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Port 3 is the coupled port where a portion of the power applied to port 1 appears.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Port 2 is the transmitted port where the power from port 1 is outputted, less the portion that went to port 3.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are frequently symmetrical so there also exists port 4, the isolated port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A portion of the power applied to port 2 will be coupled to port 4.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, the device is not normally used in this mode and port 4 is usually terminated with a matched load (typically 50 ohms).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This termination can be internal to the device and port 4 is not accessible to the user.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Effectively, this results in a 3-port device, hence the utility of the second symbol for directional couplers in figure 1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] in this article have the meaning "parameter *P* at port *a* due to an input at port *b*".
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A symbol for power dividers is shown in figure 2.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Power dividers and directional couplers are in all essentials the same class of device.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] *Directional coupler* tends to be used for 4-port devices that are only loosely coupled – that is, only a small fraction of the input power appears at the coupled port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] *Power divider* is used for devices with tight coupling (commonly, a power divider will provide half the input power at each of its output ports – a 3 dB divider) and is usually considered a 3-port device.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Common properties desired for all directional couplers are wide operational bandwidth, high directivity, and a good impedance match at all ports when the other ports are terminated in matched loads.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Some of these, and other, general characteristics are discussed below.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] where P1 is the input power at port 1 and P3 is the output power from the coupled port (see figure 1).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The coupling factor represents the primary property of a directional coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Coupling factor is a negative quantity, it cannot exceed 0 dB for a passive device, and in practice does not exceed −3 dB since more than this would result in more power output from the coupled port than power from the transmitted port – in effect their roles would be reversed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Although a negative quantity, the minus sign is frequently dropped (but still implied) in running text and diagrams and a few authors go so far as to define it as a *positive* quantity.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Coupling is not constant, but varies with frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] While different designs may reduce the variance, a perfectly flat coupler theoretically cannot be built.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are specified in terms of the coupling accuracy at the frequency band center.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The insertion loss of an ideal directional coupler will consist entirely of the coupling loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In a real directional coupler, however, the insertion loss consists of a combination of coupling loss, dielectric loss, conductor loss, and VSWR loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Depending on the frequency range, coupling loss becomes less significant above 15 dB coupling where the other losses constitute the majority of the total loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The theoretical insertion loss (dB) vs coupling (dB) for a dissipationless coupler is shown in the graph of figure 3 and the table below.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Isolation can also be defined between the two output ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In this case, one of the output ports is used as the input; the other is considered the output port while the other two ports (input and isolated) are terminated by matched loads.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The isolation between the input and the isolated ports may be different from the isolation between the two output ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For example, the isolation between ports 1 and 4 can be 30 dB while the isolation between ports 2 and 3 can be a different value such as 25 dB.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Isolation can be estimated from the coupling plus return loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The isolation should be as high as possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In actual couplers the isolated port is never completely isolated.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Waveguide directional couplers will have the best isolation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Directivity is directly related to isolation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] where: P3 is the output power from the coupled port and P4 is the power output from the isolated port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The directivity should be as high as possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The directivity is very high at the design frequency and is a more sensitive function of frequency because it depends on the cancellation of two wave components.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Waveguide directional couplers will have the best directivity.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In general, $\tau \$ and $\kappa \$ are complex, frequency dependent, numbers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The zeroes on the matrix main diagonal are a consequence of perfect matching – power input to any port is not reflected back to that same port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The zeroes on the matrix antidiagonal are a consequence of perfect isolation between the input and isolated port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] since the power entering the input port must all leave by one of the other two ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Non-zero main diagonal entries are related to return loss, and non-zero antidiagonal entries are related to isolation by similar expressions.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Some authors define the port numbers with ports 3 and 4 interchanged.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This results in a scattering matrix that is no longer all-zeroes on the antidiagonal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This terminology defines the power difference in dB between the two output ports of a 3 dB hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In an ideal hybrid circuit, the difference should be 0 dB.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, in a practical device the amplitude balance is frequency dependent and departs from the ideal 0 dB difference.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The phase difference between the two output ports of a hybrid coupler should be 0°, 90°, or 180° depending on the type used.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, like amplitude balance, the phase difference is sensitive to the input frequency and typically will vary a few degrees.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The most common form of directional coupler is a pair of coupled transmission lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] They can be realised in a number of technologies including coaxial and the planar technologies (stripline and microstrip).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] An implementation in stripline is shown in figure 4 of a quarter-wavelength (λ/4) directional coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The power on the coupled line flows in the opposite direction to the power on the main line, hence the port arrangement is not the same as shown in figure 1, but the numbering remains the same.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For this reason it is sometimes called a *backward coupler*.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The *main line* is the section between ports 1 and 2 and the *coupled line* is the section between ports 3 and 4.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Since the directional coupler is a linear device, the notations on figure 1 are arbitrary.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Any port can be the input, (an example is seen in figure 20) which will result in the directly connected port being the transmitted port, the adjacent port being the coupled port, and the diagonal port being the isolated port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] On some directional couplers, the main line is designed for high power operation (large connectors), while the coupled port may use a small connector, such as an SMA connector.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The internal load power rating may also limit operation on the coupled line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Accuracy of coupling factor depends on the dimensional tolerances for the spacing of the two coupled lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For planar printed technologies this comes down to the resolution of the printing process which determines the minimum track width that can be produced and also puts a limit on how close the lines can be placed to each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This becomes a problem when very tight coupling is required and 3 dB couplers often use a different design.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, tightly coupled lines can be produced in air stripline which also permits manufacture by printed planar technology.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In this design the two lines are printed on *opposite* sides of the dielectric rather than side by side.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The coupling of the two lines across their width is much greater than the coupling when they are edge-on to each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The λ/4 coupled-line design is good for coaxial and stripline implementations but does not work so well in the now popular microstrip format, although designs do exist.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The reason for this is that microstrip is not a homogeneous medium – there are two different mediums above and below the transmission strip.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This leads to transmission modes other than the usual TEM mode found in conductive circuits.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The propagation velocities of even and odd modes are different leading to signal dispersion.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A better solution for microstrip is a coupled line much shorter than λ/4, shown in figure 5, but this has the disadvantage of a coupling factor which rises noticeably with frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A variation of this design sometimes encountered has the coupled line a higher impedance than the main line such as shown in figure 6.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This design is advantageous where the coupler is being fed to a detector for power monitoring.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The higher impedance line results in a higher RF voltage for a given main line power making the work of the detector diode easier.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The frequency range specified by manufacturers is that of the coupled line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The main line response is much wider: for instance a coupler specified as 2–4 GHz might have a main line which could operate at 1–5 GHz.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The coupled response is periodic with frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For example, a λ/4 coupled-line coupler will have responses at *n*λ/4 where *n* is an odd integer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This preferred response gets obvious when a short impulse on the main line is followed through the coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] When the impulse on the main line reaches the coupled line a signal of the same polarity is induced on the coupled line similar to the response of an RC-high-pass.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This leads to two non-inverted pulses on the coupled line that travel in opposite direction to each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] When the pulse on the main line leaves the coupled line an inverted signal is induced on the coupled line, triggering two inverted impulses that travel in opposite direction to each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Both impulses on the coupled line that go in the same direction as the pulse on the main line are of opposite polarity.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] They cancel each other so there is no response on the exit of the coupled line in forward direction.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The pulses on the coupled line that travel in the opposite direction to the pulse on the main line are also of opposite polarity to each other but the second impulse is delayed by twice the delay of the parallel line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For a λ/4 coupled-line the total delay length is λ/2 so the second signal is inverted and this gives a maximum response on the coupled port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A single λ/4 coupled section is good for bandwidths of less than an octave.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] To achieve greater bandwidths multiple λ/4 coupling sections are used.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The design of such couplers proceeds in much the same way as the design of distributed-element filters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Ripple is the maximum variation in output of the coupled port in its passband, usually quoted as plus or minus a value in dB from the nominal coupling factor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It can be shown that coupled-line directional couplers have $\tau \$ purely real and $\kappa \$ purely imaginary at all frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This leads to a simplification of the S-matrix and the result that the coupled port is always in quadrature phase (90°) with the output port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Some applications make use of this phase difference.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The branch-line coupler consists of two parallel transmission lines physically coupled together with two or more branch lines between them.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The branch lines are spaced λ/4 apart and represent sections of a multi-section filter design in the same way as the multiple sections of a coupled-line coupler except that here the coupling of each section is controlled with the impedance of the branch lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The main and coupled line are $\scriptstyle {\sqrt {2}}$ of the system impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The more sections there are in the coupler, the higher is the ratio of impedances of the branch lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] High impedance lines have narrow tracks and this usually limits the design to three sections in planar formats due to manufacturing limitations.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A similar limitation applies for coupling factors looser than 10 dB; low coupling also requires narrow tracks.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Coupled lines are a better choice when loose coupling is required, but branch-line couplers are good for tight coupling and can be used for 3 dB hybrids.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Branch-line couplers usually do not have such a wide bandwidth as coupled lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This style of coupler is good for implementing in high-power, air dielectric, solid bar formats as the rigid structure is easy to mechanically support.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Branch line couplers can be used as crossovers as an alternative to air bridges, which in some applications cause an unacceptable amount of coupling between the lines being crossed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] An ideal branch-line crossover theoretically has no coupling between the two paths through it.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The design is a 3-branch coupler equivalent to two 3 dB 90° hybrid couplers connected in cascade.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The result is effectively a 0 dB coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It will cross over the inputs to the diagonally opposite outputs with a phase delay of 90° in both lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The construction of the Lange coupler is similar to the interdigital filter with paralleled lines interleaved to achieve the coupling.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It is used for strong couplings in the range 3 dB to 6 dB.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The earliest transmission line power dividers were simple T-junctions.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] These suffer from very poor isolation between the output ports – a large part of the power reflected back from port 2 finds its way into port 3.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It can be shown that it is not theoretically possible to simultaneously match all three ports of a passive, lossless three-port and poor isolation is unavoidable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The term *hybrid coupler* originally applied to 3 dB coupled-line directional couplers, that is, directional couplers in which the two outputs are each half the input power.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This synonymously meant a quadrature 3 dB coupler with outputs 90° out of phase.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Now any matched 4-port with isolated arms and equal power division is called a hybrid or hybrid coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Other types can have different phase relationships.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In this article *hybrid coupler* without qualification means a coupled-line hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Wilkinson power divider consists of two parallel *uncoupled* λ/4 transmission lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The input is fed to both lines in parallel and the outputs are terminated with twice the system impedance bridged between them.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Wilkinson power divider solves the matching problem of the simple T-junction: it has low VSWR at all ports and high isolation between output ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The input and output impedances at each port are designed to be equal to the characteristic impedance of the microwave system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Coupled-line directional couplers are described above.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] When the coupling is designed to be 3 dB it is called a hybrid coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The two output ports have a 90° phase difference (-*i* to −1) and so this is a 90° hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring coupler, also called the rat-race coupler, is a four-port 3 dB directional coupler consisting of a 3λ/2 ring of transmission line with four lines at the intervals shown in figure 12.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Power input at port 1 splits and travels both ways round the ring.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] At ports 2 and 3 the signal arrives in phase and adds whereas at port 4 it is out of phase and cancels.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Ports 2 and 3 are in phase with each other, hence this is an example of a 0° hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Figure 12 shows a planar implementation but this design can also be implemented in coax or waveguide.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring is not symmetric on its ports; choosing a different port as the input does not necessarily produce the same results.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] With port 1 or port 3 as the input the hybrid ring is a 0° hybrid as stated.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However using port 2 or port 4 as the input results in a 180° hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This fact leads to another useful application of the hybrid ring: it can be used to produce sum (Σ) and difference (Δ) signals from two input signals as shown in figure 12.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] With inputs to ports 2 and 3, the Σ signal appears at port 1 and the Δ signal appears at port 4.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A typical power divider is shown in figure 13.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Ideally, input power would be divided equally between the output ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Dividers are made up of multiple couplers and, like couplers, may be reversed and used as multiplexers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The drawback is that for a four channel multiplexer, the output consists of only 1/4 the power from each, and is relatively inefficient.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The reason for this is that at each combiner half the input power goes to port 4 and is dissipated in the termination load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] If the two inputs were coherent the phases could be so arranged that cancellation occurred at port 4 and then all the power would go to port 1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, multiplexer inputs are usually from entirely independent sources and therefore not coherent.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Lossless multiplexing can only be done with filter networks.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The branch-line coupler described above can also be implemented in waveguide.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] One of the most common, and simplest, waveguide directional couplers is the Bethe-hole directional coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This consists of two parallel waveguides, one stacked on top of the other, with a hole between them.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Some of the power from one guide is launched through the hole into the other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Bethe-hole coupler is another example of a backward coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The concept of the Bethe-hole coupler can be extended by providing multiple holes.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The design of such couplers has parallels with the multiple section coupled transmission lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Using multiple holes allows the bandwidth to be extended by designing the sections as a Butterworth, Chebyshev, or some other filter class.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The hole size is chosen to give the desired coupling for each section of the filter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Design criteria are to achieve a substantially flat coupling together with high directivity over the desired band.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Riblet short-slot coupler is two waveguides side-by-side with the side-wall in common instead of the long side as in the Bethe-hole coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A slot is cut in the sidewall to allow coupling.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This design is frequently used to produce a 3 dB coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Schwinger reversed-phase coupler is another design using parallel waveguides, this time the long side of one is common with the short side-wall of the other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Two off-centre slots are cut between the waveguides spaced λ/4 apart.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This design has the advantage of a substantially flat directivity response and the disadvantage of a strongly frequency-dependent coupling compared to the Bethe-hole coupler, which has little variation in coupling factor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Moreno crossed-guide coupler has two waveguides stacked one on top of the other like the Bethe-hole coupler but at right angles to each other instead of parallel.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Two off-centre holes, usually cross-shaped are cut on the diagonal between the waveguides a distance $\scriptstyle {\sqrt {2}}\lambda /4$ apart.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The Moreno coupler is good for tight coupling applications.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It is a compromise between the properties of the Bethe-hole and Schwinger couplers with both coupling and directivity varying with frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring discussed above can also be implemented in waveguide.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Coherent power division was first accomplished by means of simple Tee junctions.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] At microwave frequencies, waveguide tees have two possible forms – the E-plane and H-plane.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] These two junctions split power equally, but because of the different field configurations at the junction, the electric fields at the output arms are in phase for the H-plane tee and are 180° out of phase for the E-plane tee.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The combination of these two tees to form a hybrid tee is known as the magic tee.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The magic tee is a four-port component which can perform the vector sum (Σ) and difference (Δ) of two coherent microwave signals.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The standard 3 dB hybrid transformer is shown in figure 16.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Power at port 1 is split equally between ports 2 and 3 but in antiphase to each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The hybrid transformer is therefore a 180° hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The centre-tap is usually terminated internally but it is possible to bring it out as port 4; in which case the hybrid can be used as a sum and difference hybrid.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, port 4 presents as a different impedance to the other ports and will require an additional transformer for impedance conversion if it is required to use this port at the same system impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Hybrid transformers are commonly used in telecommunications for 2 to 4 wire conversion.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Telephone handsets include such a converter to convert the 2-wire line to the 4 wires from the earpiece and mouthpiece.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For lower frequencies (less than 600 MHz) a compact broadband implementation by means of RF transformers is possible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In figure 17 a circuit is shown which is meant for weak coupling and can be understood along these lines: A signal is coming in one line pair.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] One transformer reduces the voltage of the signal the other reduces the current.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The same argument holds for every other direction of a signal through the coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The relative sign of the induced voltage and current determines the direction of the outgoing signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] is the secondary to primary turns ratio.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For a 3 dB coupling, that is equal splitting of the signal between the transmitted port and the coupled port, $\scriptstyle n={\sqrt {2}}$ and the isolated port is terminated in twice the characteristic impedance – 100 Ω for a 50 Ω system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A 3 dB power divider based on this circuit has the two outputs in 180° phase to each other, compared to λ/4 coupled lines which have a 90° phase relationship.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A simple tee circuit of resistors can be used as a power divider as shown in figure 18.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This circuit can also be implemented as a delta circuit by applying the Y-Δ transform.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The delta form uses resistors that are equal to the system impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This can be advantageous because precision resistors of the value of the system impedance are always available for most system nominal impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The tee circuit has the benefits of simplicity, low cost, and intrinsically wide bandwidth.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It has two major drawbacks; first, the circuit will dissipate power since it is resistive: an equal split will result in 6 dB insertion loss instead of 3 dB.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The second problem is that there is 0 dB directivity leading to very poor isolation between the output ports.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The insertion loss is not such a problem for an unequal split of power: for instance -40 dB at port 3 has an insertion loss less than 0.2 dB at port 2.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Isolation can be improved at the expense of insertion loss at both output ports by replacing the output resistors with T pads.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The isolation improvement is greater than the insertion loss added.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] A true hybrid divider/coupler with, theoretically, infinite isolation and directivity can be made from a resistive bridge circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Like the tee circuit, the bridge has 6 dB insertion loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] It has the disadvantage that it cannot be used with unbalanced circuits without the addition of transformers; however, it is ideal for 600 Ω balanced telecommunication lines if the insertion loss is not an issue.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The resistors in the bridge which represent ports are not usually part of the device (with the exception of port 4 which may well be left permanently terminated internally) these being provided by the line terminations.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The device thus consists essentially of two resistors (plus the port 4 termination).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The above 6 dB coupler can be generalized to couplers with arbitrary coupling ratio.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Consider the following 5 resistor bridge circuit, where the resistor ratios $r=R_{5}/R_{2}=R_{3}/R_{6}$ of the 2 arms are equal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In typical application, drive resistance $R_{1}=Z_{0}$ is the characteristic impedance, typically 50 $\Omega$ in radiowave and microwave circuits.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Port 2 and 3 are not internal to the hybrid, rather, they are connected to external loads, typically $R_{2}=R_{3}=Z_{0}$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Under these conditions, the entire circuit has an input impedance of $Z_{0}$ , i.e. port 1 sees a matched load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The coupling port (P3) voltage ratio is $r/(1+r)$ , the through port (P2) voltage ratio is $1/(1+r)$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This circuit has a theoretical infinite reverse isolation when $R_{4}=Z_{0}$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] To see this, connect port 2 to a floating source.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The bridge is balanced and there is no voltage across port 3, i.e. infinite reverse isolation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] One disadvantage is of this hybrid is that only port 1 and 3 are ground referenced.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] When using single ended sources and loads, port 2 needs to be transformed from ground referenced to floating.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This can be done with a balun or specifically, a common-mode choke.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This can be further extended to a full 4 port hybrid coupler by connecting two hybrids back to back, sharing the same balun.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The coupled output from the directional coupler can be used to monitor frequency and power level on the signal without interrupting the main power flow in the system (except for a power reduction – see figure 3).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] If isolation is high, directional couplers are good for combining signals to feed a single line to a receiver for two-tone receiver tests.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In figure 20, one signal enters port P3 and one enters port P2, while both exit port P1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The signal from port P3 to port P1 will experience 10 dB of loss, and the signal from port P2 to port P1 will have 0.5 dB loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The internal load on the isolated port will dissipate the signal losses from port P3 and port P2.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] If the isolators in figure 20 are neglected, the isolation measurement (port P2 to port P3) determines the amount of power from the signal generator F2 that will be injected into the signal generator F1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] As the injection level increases, it may cause modulation of signal generator F1, or even injection phase locking.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Because of the symmetry of the directional coupler, the reverse injection will happen with the same possible modulation problems of signal generator F2 by F1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Therefore, the isolators are used in figure 20 to effectively increase the isolation (or directivity) of the directional coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Consequently, the injection loss will be the isolation of the directional coupler plus the reverse isolation of the isolator.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Applications of the hybrid include monopulse comparators, mixers, power combiners, dividers, modulators, and phased array radar antenna systems.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Both in-phase devices (such as the Wilkinson divider) and quadrature (90°) hybrid couplers may be used for coherent power divider applications.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] An example of quadrature hybrids being used in a coherent power combiner application is given in the next section.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] An inexpensive version of the power divider, shown in figure 16, is used in the home to divide cable TV or over-the-air TV signals to multiple TV sets and other devices.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Multiport splitters with more than two output ports usually consist internally of a number of cascaded couplers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Domestic broadband internet service can be provided by cable TV companies (cable internet).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The domestic user's internet cable modem is connected to one port of the splitter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Since hybrid circuits are bi-directional, they can be used to coherently combine power as well as splitting it.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] In figure 21, an example is shown of a signal split up to feed multiple low power amplifiers, then recombined to feed a single antenna with high power.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The phases of the inputs to each power combiner are arranged such that the two inputs are 90° out of phase with each other.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Since the coupled port of a hybrid combiner is 90° out of phase with the transmitted port, this causes the powers to add at the output of the combiner and to cancel at the isolated port: a representative example from figure 21 is shown in figure 22.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Note that there is an additional fixed 90° phase shift to both ports at each combiner/divider which is not shown in the diagrams for simplicity.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Applying in-phase power to both input ports would not get the desired result: the quadrature sum of the two inputs would appear at both output ports – that is half the total power out of each.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This approach allows the use of numerous less expensive and lower-power amplifiers in the circuitry instead of a single high-power TWT.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Yet another approach is to have each solid state amplifier (SSA) feed an antenna and let the power be combined in space or be used to feed a lens attached to an antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The phase properties of a 90° hybrid coupler can be used to great advantage in microwave circuits.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] For example, in a balanced microwave amplifier the two input stages are fed through a hybrid coupler.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The FET device normally has a very poor match and reflects much of the incident energy.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] However, since the devices are essentially identical the reflection coefficients from each device are equal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] The reflected voltage from the FETs are in phase at the isolated port and are 180° different at the input port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Therefore, all of the reflected power from the FETs goes to the load at the isolated port and no power goes to the input port.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] This results in a good input match (low VSWR).
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] If phase-matched lines are used for an antenna input to a 180° hybrid coupler as shown in figure 23, a null will occur directly between the antennas.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] To receive a signal in that position, one would have to either change the hybrid type or line length.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] To reject a signal from a given direction, or create the difference pattern for a monopulse radar, this is a good approach.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] Phase-difference couplers can be used to create beam tilt in a VHF FM radio station, by delaying the phase to the lower elements of an antenna array.
[src:smith-chart-matching/directional-coupler] More generally, phase-difference couplers, together with fixed phase delays and antenna arrays, are used in beam-forming networks such as the Butler matrix, to create a radio beam in any prescribed direction.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In electrical engineering, **impedance matching** is the practice of designing or adjusting the input impedance or output impedance of an electrical device for a desired value.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Often, the desired value is selected to maximize power transfer or minimize signal reflection.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For example, impedance matching typically is used to improve power transfer from a radio transmitter via the interconnecting transmission line to the antenna.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Signals on a transmission line will be transmitted without reflections if the transmission line is terminated with a matching impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Techniques of impedance matching include transformers, adjustable networks of lumped resistance, capacitance and inductance, or properly proportioned transmission lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Practical impedance-matching devices will generally provide best results over a specified frequency band.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The concept of impedance matching is widespread in electrical engineering, but is relevant in other applications in which a form of energy, not necessarily electrical, is transferred between a source and a load, such as in acoustics or optics.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Impedance characterizes the ratio of energy components in a given domain.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For constant signals, this impedance can also be constant.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For varying signals, it usually changes with frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The energy involved can be electrical, mechanical, acoustic, magnetic, electromagnetic, or thermal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The concept of electrical impedance is perhaps the most commonly known.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Electrical impedance, like electrical resistance, is measured in ohms.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In general, impedance (symbol: *Z*) has a complex value; this means that loads generally have a resistance component (symbol: *R*) which forms the real part and a reactance component (symbol: *X*) which forms the imaginary part.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This impedance characterizes the ratio between the voltage and current components in the medium.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In simple cases (such as low-frequency or direct current power transmission) the reactance may be negligible or zero; the impedance can be considered a pure resistance, expressed as a real number.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In the following summary we will consider the general case when resistance and reactance are both significant, and the special case in which the reactance is negligible.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Complex conjugate matching is used when maximum power transfer is required, namely $Z_{\text{load}}=Z_{\text{source}}^{*},$ where a superscript * indicates the complex conjugate.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A conjugate match is different from a reflection-less match when either the source or load has a reactive component.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the source has a reactive component, but the load is purely resistive, then matching can be achieved by adding a reactance of the same magnitude but opposite sign to the load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This simple matching network, consisting of a single element, will usually achieve a perfect match at only a single frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This is because the added element will either be a capacitor or an inductor, whose impedance in both cases is frequency dependent, and will not, in general, follow the frequency dependence of the source impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For wide bandwidth applications, a more complex network must be designed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For two impedances to be complex conjugates their resistances must be equal, and their reactances must be equal in magnitude but of opposite signs.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In low-frequency or DC systems (or systems with purely resistive sources and loads) the reactances are zero, or small enough to be ignored.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In this case, maximum power transfer occurs when the resistance of the load is equal to the resistance of the source (see maximum power theorem for a mathematical proof).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Impedance matching is not always necessary.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For example, if delivering a high voltage (to reduce signal degradation or to reduce power consumption) is more important than maximizing power transfer, then *impedance bridging* or *voltage bridging* is often used.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In older audio systems (reliant on transformers and passive filter networks, and based on the telephone system), the source and load resistances were matched at 600 ohms.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] One reason for this was to maximize power transfer, as there were no amplifiers available that could restore lost signal.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Another reason was to ensure correct operation of the hybrid transformers used at central exchange equipment to separate outgoing from incoming speech, so these could be amplified or fed to a four-wire circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Most modern audio circuits, on the other hand, use active amplification and filtering and can use voltage-bridging connections for greatest accuracy.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Strictly speaking, impedance matching only applies when both source and load devices are linear; however, matching may be obtained between nonlinear devices within certain operating ranges.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Adjusting the source impedance or the load impedance, in general, is called "impedance matching".
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] There are a variety of devices used between a source of energy and a load that perform "impedance matching".
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] To match electrical impedances, engineers use combinations of transformers, resistors, inductors, capacitors and transmission lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] These passive (and active) impedance-matching devices are optimized for different applications and include baluns, antenna tuners (sometimes called ATUs or roller-coasters, because of their appearance), acoustic horns, matching networks, and terminators.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Transformers are sometimes used to match the impedances of circuits.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A transformer converts alternating current at one voltage to the same waveform at another voltage.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The power input to the transformer and output from the transformer is the same (except for conversion losses).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The side with the lower voltage is at low impedance (because this has the lower number of turns), and the side with the higher voltage is at a higher impedance (as it has more turns in its coil).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] One example of this method involves a television balun transformer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This transformer allows interfacing a balanced line (300-ohm twin-lead) and an unbalanced line (75-ohm coaxial cable such as RG-6).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] To match the impedances, both cables must be connected to a matching transformer with a turns ratio of 2:1.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In this example, the 300-ohm line is connected to the transformer side with more turns; the 75-ohm cable is connected to the transformer side with fewer turns.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Resistive impedance matches are easiest to design and can be achieved with a simple L pad consisting of two resistors.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Power loss is an unavoidable consequence of using resistive networks, and they are only (usually) used to transfer line level signals.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Most lumped-element devices can match a specific range of load impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For example, in order to match an inductive load into a real impedance, a capacitor needs to be used.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the load impedance becomes capacitive, the matching element must be replaced by an inductor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In many cases, there is a need to use the same circuit to match a broad range of load impedance and thus simplify the circuit design.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This issue was addressed by the stepped transmission line, where multiple, serially placed, quarter-wave dielectric slugs are used to vary a transmission line's characteristic impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] By controlling the position of each element, a broad range of load impedances can be matched without having to reconnect the circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Filters are frequently used to achieve impedance matching in telecommunications and radio engineering.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In general, it is not theoretically possible to achieve perfect impedance matching at all frequencies with a network of discrete components.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Impedance matching networks are designed with a definite bandwidth, take the form of a filter, and use filter theory in their design.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Applications requiring only a narrow bandwidth, such as radio tuners and transmitters, might use a simple tuned filter such as a stub.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This would provide a perfect match at one specific frequency only.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Wide bandwidth matching requires filters with multiple sections.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A simple electrical impedance-matching network requires one capacitor and one inductor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In the figure to the right, R1 > R2, however, either R1 or R2 may be the source and the other the load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] One of X1 or X2 must be an inductor and the other must be a capacitor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] One reactance is in parallel with the source (or load), and the other is in series with the load (or source).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If a reactance is in parallel *with the source*, the effective network matches from high to low impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Consider a real source impedance of $R_{1}$ and real load impedance of $R_{2}$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Note, $X_{1}$ , the reactance in parallel, has a negative reactance because it is typically a capacitor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This gives the L-network the additional feature of harmonic suppression since it is a low pass filter too.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The inverse connection (impedance step-up) is simply the reverse—for example, reactance in series with the source.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The magnitude of the impedance ratio is limited by reactance losses such as the Q of the inductor.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Multiple L-sections can be wired in cascade to achieve higher impedance ratios or greater bandwidth.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Transmission line matching networks can be modeled as infinitely many L-sections wired in cascade.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Optimal matching circuits can be designed for a particular system using Smith charts.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Power factor correction devices are intended to cancel the reactive and nonlinear characteristics of a load at the end of a power line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This causes the load seen by the power line to be purely resistive.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For a given true power required by a load this minimizes the true current supplied through the power lines, and minimizes power wasted in the resistance of those power lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For example, a maximum power point tracker is used to extract the maximum power from a solar panel and efficiently transfer it to batteries, the power grid or other loads.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The maximum power theorem applies to its "upstream" connection to the solar panel, so it emulates a load resistance equal to the solar panel source resistance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] However, the maximum power theorem does not apply to its "downstream" connection.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] That connection is an impedance bridging connection; it emulates a high-voltage, low-resistance source to maximize efficiency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] On the power grid the overall load is usually inductive.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Consequently, power factor correction is most commonly achieved with banks of capacitors.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] It is only necessary for correction to be achieved at one single frequency, the frequency of the supply.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Complex networks are only required when a band of frequencies must be matched and this is the reason why simple capacitors are all that is usually required for power factor correction.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In RF connections, impedance matching is desirable, because otherwise reflections may be created at the end of the mismatched transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The reflection may cause frequency-dependent loss.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In radio-frequency (RF) systems, a common value for source and load impedances is 50 ohms.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A typical RF load is a quarter-wave ground plane antenna (37 ohms with an ideal ground plane).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] so the reflection coefficient is the same (except for sign), no matter from which direction the wave approaches the boundary.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] There is also a current reflection coefficient, which is the negative of the voltage reflection coefficient.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the wave encounters an open at the load end, positive voltage and negative current pulses are transmitted back toward the source (negative current means the current is going the opposite direction).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Thus, at each boundary there are four reflection coefficients (voltage and current on one side, and voltage and current on the other side).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] All four are the same, except that two are positive and two are negative.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The voltage reflection coefficient and current reflection coefficient on the same side have opposite signs.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Voltage reflection coefficients on opposite sides of the boundary have opposite signs.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Because they are all the same except for sign it is traditional to interpret the reflection coefficient as the voltage reflection coefficient (unless otherwise indicated).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Either end (or both ends) of a transmission line can be a source or a load (or both), so there is no inherent preference for which side of the boundary is medium 1 and which side is medium 2.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] With a single transmission line it is customary to define the voltage reflection coefficient for a wave incident on the boundary from the transmission line side, regardless of whether a source or load is connected on the other side.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In a transmission line, a wave travels from the source along the line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Suppose the wave hits a boundary (an abrupt change in impedance).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Some of the wave is reflected back, while some keeps moving onwards.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is incident on the boundary from the source side.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is transmitted to the load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is reflected back toward the source.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] where $\Gamma _{TL}\,$ is the reflection coefficient going from the transmission line to the load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The source of waves incident from the line are the reflections from the load end.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the source impedance matches the line, reflections from the load end will be absorbed at the source end.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the transmission line is not matched at both ends reflections from the load will be re-reflected at the source and re-re-reflected at the load end *ad infinitum*, losing energy on each transit of the transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This can cause a resonance condition and strongly frequency-dependent behavior.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In a narrow-band system this can be desirable for matching, but is generally undesirable in a wide-band system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] where $T\ ,$ is the one-way transfer function (from either end to the other) when the transmission line is exactly matched at source and load. $T\,$ accounts for everything that happens to the signal in transit (including delay, attenuation and dispersion).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] where $V_{S}\,$ is the open circuit (or unloaded) output voltage from the source.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Telephone systems also use matched impedances to minimise echo on long-distance lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This is related to transmission-line theory.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Matching also enables the telephone *hybrid coil* (2- to 4-wire conversion) to operate correctly.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] As the signals are sent and received on the same two-wire circuit to the central office (or exchange), cancellation is necessary at the telephone earpiece so excessive sidetone is not heard.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] All devices used in telephone signal paths are generally dependent on matched cable, source and load impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In the local loop, the impedance chosen is 600 ohms (nominal).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Terminating networks are installed at the exchange to offer the best match to their subscriber lines.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Each country has its own standard for these networks, but they are all designed to approximate about 600 ohms over the voice frequency band.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Audio amplifiers typically do not match impedances, but provide an output impedance that is lower than the load impedance (such as < 0.1 ohm in typical semiconductor amplifiers), for improved speaker damping.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For vacuum tube amplifiers, impedance-changing transformers are often used to get a low output impedance, and to better match the amplifier's performance to the load impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Some tube amplifiers have output transformer taps to adapt the amplifier output to typical loudspeaker impedances.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The impedance of the loudspeaker on the secondary coil of the transformer will be transformed to a higher impedance on the primary coil in the circuit of the power pentodes by the square of the turns ratio, which forms the *impedance scaling factor*.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The output stage in common-drain or common-collector semiconductor-based end stages with MOSFETs or power transistors has a very low output impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If they are properly balanced, there is no need for a transformer or a large electrolytic capacitor to separate AC from DC current.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In NMR techniques (NMR spectroscopy and MR imaging), impedance matching is required to adjust power transfer to the radiofrequency antenna depending on the sample present in the system.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] It is typically performed automatically (in clinical imaging systems for instance) or manually, before acquisitions take place.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The radiofrequency antennas are equipped with variable "match" and "tune" adjusting screws which enable the user or the system to adjust the center frequency and the level of power transfer at the same time.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Similar to electrical transmission lines, an impedance matching problem exists when transferring sound energy from one medium to another.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the acoustic impedance of the two media are very different most sound energy will be reflected (or absorbed), rather than transferred across the border.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The gel used in medical ultrasonography helps transfer acoustic energy from the transducer to the body and back again.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Without the gel, the impedance mismatch in the transducer-to-air and the air-to-body discontinuity reflects almost all the energy, leaving very little to go into the body.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The bones in the middle ear function as a series of levers, which matches mechanical impedance between the eardrum (which is acted upon by vibrations in air) and the fluid-filled inner ear.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Horns in loudspeaker systems are used like transformers in electrical circuits to match the impedance of the transducer to the impedance of the air.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This principle is used in both horn loudspeakers and musical instruments.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Because most driver impedances are poorly matched to the impedance of free air at low frequencies, loudspeaker enclosures are designed to both match impedance and minimize destructive phase cancellations between output from the front and rear of a speaker cone.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The loudness of sound produced in air from a loudspeaker is directly related to the ratio of the diameter of the speaker to the wavelength of the sound being produced: larger speakers can produce lower frequencies at a higher level than smaller speakers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Elliptical speakers are a complex case, acting like large speakers lengthwise and small speakers crosswise.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Acoustic impedance matching (or the lack of it) affects the operation of a megaphone, an echo and soundproofing.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A similar effect occurs when light (or any electromagnetic wave) hits the interface between two media with different refractive indices.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic materials, the refractive index is inversely proportional to the material's characteristic impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] to calculate reflection and transmission coefficients for the interface.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic dielectrics, this equation is equivalent to the Fresnel equations.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Unwanted reflections can be reduced by the use of an anti-reflection optical coating.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If a body of mass *m* collides elastically with a second body, maximum energy transfer to the second body will occur when the second body has the same mass *m*.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In a head-on collision of equal masses, the energy of the first body will be completely transferred to the second body (as in Newton's cradle for example).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] In this case, the masses act as "mechanical impedances", which must be matched to maximize energy transfer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] which is analogous to the power-transfer equation.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If we cannot change the masses of bodies, then we can match their impedance with a lever.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] Imagine a large ball dropping to the ground, and a small ball lying on the ground.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The large ball hits the short end of a lever, and the small ball is launched from the long end of the lever.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If the lever arm lengths satisfy $l_{1}m_{1}=l_{2}m_{2}$ , then all energy would be transferred to the small ball if collisions are elastic.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] This is roughly how the middle ear works (see above).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] These principles are useful in the application of highly energetic materials (explosives).
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] If an explosive charge is placed on a target, the sudden release of energy causes compression waves to propagate through the target radially from the point-charge contact.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] When the compression waves reach areas of high acoustic impedance mismatch (such as the opposite side of the target), tension waves reflect back and create spalling.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] The greater the mismatch, the greater the effect of creasing and spalling will be.
[src:smith-chart-matching/impedance-matching] A charge initiated against a wall with air behind it will do more damage to the wall than a charge initiated against a wall with soil behind it.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] A **quarter-wave impedance transformer**, often written as **λ/4 impedance transformer**, is a transmission line or waveguide used in electrical engineering of length one-quarter wavelength (λ), terminated with some known impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] It presents at its input the dual of the impedance with which it is terminated.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Alternatives to the quarter-wave impedance transformer include lumped circuits that can produce the impedance inverter function, and stubs for impedance matching.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] It is especially useful for making an inductor out of a capacitor, since designers have a preference for the latter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Another application is when DC power needs to be fed into a transmission line, which may be necessary to power an active device connected to the line, such as a switching transistor or a varactor diode for instance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] An ideal DC voltage source has zero impedance, that is, it presents a short circuit and it is not useful to connect a short circuit directly across the line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Feeding in the DC via a λ/4 transformer will transform the short circuit into an open circuit which has no effect on the signals on the line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Likewise, an open circuit can be transformed into a short circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] The device can be used as a component in a filter, and in this application it is sometimes known as an inverter because it produces the mathematical inverse of an impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Impedance inverters are not to be confused with the more common meaning of power inverter for a device that has the inverse function of a rectifier.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Inverter is a general term for the class of circuits that have the function of inverting an impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] There are many such circuits and the term does not necessarily imply a λ/4 transformer.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] The most common use for inverters is to convert a 2-element-kind *LC* filter design such as a ladder network into a one-element-kind filter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Equally, for bandpass filters, a two-resonator-kind (resonators and anti-resonators) filter can be converted to a one-resonator-kind.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Inverters are classified as *K*-inverters or *J*-inverters depending on whether they are inverting a series impedance or a shunt admittance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Filters incorporating λ/4 inverters are only suitable for narrow band applications.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] This is because the impedance transformer line only has the correct electrical length of λ/4 at one specific frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] The further the signal is from this frequency the less accurately the impedance transformer will be reproducing the impedance inverter function and the less accurately it will be representing the element values of the original lumped-element filter design.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] A transmission line that is terminated in some impedance, *Z*L, that is different from the characteristic impedance, *Z*0, will result in a wave being reflected from the termination back to the source.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] At the input to the line the reflected voltage adds to the incident voltage and the reflected current subtracts (because the wave is travelling in the opposite direction) from the incident current.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] Similar properties can be realized using either a "T" or "PI" network consisting of lumped elements each of which has a reactance equal to the Zo of the simulated one-quarter wavelength (λ), transmission line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] This realization of the transformer is useful at lower frequencies where a quarter-wave transmission line would be impractically long.
[src:smith-chart-matching/quarter-wave-impedance-transformer] The quarter wave transformer is a subset of series line (section) matching methods.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] In microwave and radio-frequency engineering, a **stub** or **resonant stub** is a transmission line or waveguide connected at one end only.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The free end of the stub is either left open-circuit, or short-circuited (as is always the case for waveguides).
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Neglecting transmission line losses, the input impedance of the stub is purely reactive; either capacitive or inductive, depending on the electrical length of the stub, and on whether it is open or short circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stubs may thus function as capacitors, inductors and resonant circuits at radio frequencies.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The behaviour of stubs is due to standing waves along their length.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Their reactive properties are determined by their physical length in relation to the wavelength of the radio waves.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Therefore, stubs are most commonly used in UHF or microwave circuits in which the wavelengths are short enough that the stub is conveniently small.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] They are often used to replace discrete capacitors and inductors, because at UHF and microwave frequencies lumped components perform poorly due to parasitic reactance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stubs are commonly used in antenna impedance matching circuits, frequency selective filters, and resonant circuits for UHF electronic oscillators and RF amplifiers.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stubs can be constructed with any type of transmission line: parallel conductor line (where they are called Lecher lines), coaxial cable, stripline, waveguide, and dielectric waveguide.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stub circuits can be designed using a Smith chart, a graphical tool which can determine what length line to use to obtain a desired reactance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Thus, depending on whether $\ \tan(\beta \ell )\$ is positive or negative, the short circuited stub will be inductive or capacitive, respectively.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] where in both equations, n is an integer number of half-wavelengths (possibly zero) that can be arbitrarily added to the line without changing the impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] where the symbols $\ Z_{0},\beta ,\ell ,\omega ,\$ etc. used in this section have the same meaning as in the section above.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] It follows that depending on whether $\cot(\beta \ell )$ is positive or negative, the stub will be capacitive or inductive, respectively.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] where again, n is an arbitrary whole number of half-wavelengths that can be inserted into the segment (including zero).
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stubs are often used as resonant circuits in oscillators and distributed element filters.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] An open circuit stub of length $\ \ell$ will have a capacitive impedance at low frequency when $\ \beta \ell <\pi /2$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Above this frequency the impedance is inductive.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] At precisely $\beta \ell =\pi /2$ the stub presents a short circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] This is qualitatively the same behaviour as a series resonant circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] where $\ v$ is the velocity of propagation and is constant with frequency for a lossless line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] While stubs function as resonant circuits, they differ from lumped element resonant circuits in that they have multiple resonant frequencies; in addition to the fundamental resonant frequency $\ \omega _{0}\,$ , they resonate at multiples of this frequency: $\ n\omega _{0}\,$ .
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The impedance will not continue to rise monotonically with frequency after resonance as in a lumped tuned circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] It will rise until the point where $\ \beta l=\pi$ at which point it will be open circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] After this point (which is an anti-resonance point), the impedance will again become capacitive and start to fall.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] It will continue to fall until at $\ \beta l=3\pi /2\,$ it again presents a short circuit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] At this point, the filtering action of the stub has failed.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] This response of the stub continues to repeat with increasing frequency alternating between resonance and anti-resonance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] It is not only a characteristic of stubs but of all distributed element filters that there is some frequency beyond which the filter fails and multiple unwanted passbands are produced.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Similarly, a short circuit stub is an anti-resonator at $\ \pi /2$ , that is, it behaves as a parallel resonant circuit, but again fails as $\ 3\pi /2$ is approached.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Stubs can match a load impedance to the transmission line characteristic impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The stub is positioned a distance from the load.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] This distance is chosen so that at that point, the resistive part of the load impedance is made equal to the resistive part of the characteristic impedance by impedance transformer action of the length of the main line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The length of the stub is chosen so that it exactly cancels the reactive part of the presented impedance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The stub is made capacitive or inductive according to whether the main line presents an inductive or capacitive impedance, respectively.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] This is not the same as the actual impedance of the load since the reactive part of the load impedance will be subject to impedance transformer action and the resistive part.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Matching stubs can be made adjustable so that matching can be corrected on test.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] A single stub will only achieve a perfect match at one specific frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Multiple stubs can be placed along the main transmission line to achieve wideband matching.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] This creates a structure similar to a filter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Filter design methods, such as Chebyshev filter design, may be used, but the focus is on impedance matching rather than passband performance.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] The resulting transmission function of the network has a passband ripple like the Chebyshev filter, but the ripples never reach 0 dB insertion loss at any point in the passband, as they would do for the standard filter.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Radial stubs are a planar component that consists of a sector of a circle rather than a constant-width line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] They are used with planar transmission lines when a low impedance stub is required.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Low characteristic impedance lines require a wide line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] With a wide line, the junction of the stub with the main line is not at a well-defined point.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Radial stubs overcome this difficulty by narrowing to a point at the junction.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Filter circuits using stubs often use them in pairs, one connected to each side of the main line.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] A pair of radial stubs so connected is called a butterfly stub or a bowtie stub.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Open circuit stubs can inadvertently be created in the design of printed circuit boards.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] A 1⁄4-wavelength stub would completely cancel out the desired signal and historically the elimination of extraneous conductors have managed to avoid this issue.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] However, higher-frequency signaling on the order of 12 Gbps (6 GHz) have greatly decreased the length of the stub required to reach 1⁄4-wavelength, making vias a new common culprit.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Since the 2020s, backdrilling is used to shorten vias so that they do not affect the intended signal frequency.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] Elimination of extraneous conductors may run contrary to a desire to make a device extensible or more easily testable.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] For example, it used to be common practice to leave openings on computer memory buses where additional DIMM (memory modules) can be plugged in.
[src:smith-chart-matching/stub-electronics] However, at DDR5/LPDDR5 data rates, the stubs become a limiting factor for achieving higher signaling frequencies.
